      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "The continuum finite element model employs linear-elastic isotropic material models for titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) and UHMWPE test blocks, which are appropriate for the pre-yield regime targeted by the QoIs. Contact between screw and block is modeled with frictional contact (mu=0.2) consistent with published literature. The model form has been validated in prior FDA studies on similar spinal implant constructs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, Poisson's ratio, yield strength) were sourced from ASTM material certifications for the specific Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used in implant manufacture. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated CMM measurements of production screws. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that ±5% variation in elastic modulus produces less than 2% change in predicted stiffness, demonstrating low input sensitivity for this QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories, providing inter-laboratory reproducibility data. All screws were manufactured from the same production lot and inspected per IQ/OQ protocols. Dimensional measurements confirmed constructs were within design tolerances. The sample size exceeds the minimum recommended for statistical comparison against simulation predictions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of ASTM F1717 conditions (quasi-static, room temperature, displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min). While this matches the intended COU loading scenario, only a single test condition was evaluated. The required level of 3 was not achieved because no parametric variation of test conditions (e.g., loading rate, temperature, or fixture geometry) was performed to characterize condition sensitivity."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A formal parameter equivalency assessment was performed mapping each experimental test parameter (screw geometry, block material, fixture dimensions, loading point) to the corresponding FEA input. All parameters were confirmed equivalent within measurement uncertainty. Traceability matrix documented in Appendix B of the simulation report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 10.1 validation metric (E/uval). For all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm), E/uval < 1.96, confirming that model prediction error is within combined experimental and simulation uncertainty at the 95% confidence level. Percent differences were 4.2%, 6.8%, and 7.5% respectively, all below the 10% acceptance bound."
    },
